ng up agencies like Cradle Fund &amp; MaGIC.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>One of the most notable things&nbsp;<a href=\"https://s3-ap-southeast-1.amazonaws.com/xremo.com.my/blog-article-there-no-such-thing-as-an-original-idea-and_9-other-lessons-msian-startups-taught-me.html?X-Amz-Date=20160214T135245Z&amp;X-Amz-Expires=300&amp;X-Amz-Algorithm=AWS4-HMAC-SHA256&amp;X-Amz-Signature=bb57f4cf5b54fc431f298828e3468aaf036699caa675c8cabd39deec3db6f8d2&amp;X-Amz-Credential=ASIAIZV2KXWN4LIRWHDQ/20160214/ap-southeast-1/s3/aws4_request&amp;X-Amz-SignedHeaders=Host&amp;x-amz-security-token=AQoDYXdzEFQakAPxCOWTa5/XPgGqdq4iKPRJ8tMrT9kEncvBJWjh2gf43lNGtI%2Bnjoif3tKYDZ9g0ofIB4vOg59iIYiHf3nbdvdu%2BdBbfE6yoXhWZVhCY%2BxeoAX07oTgGCQkSMVXfMxatzGSJtJ7/JVJdUobvjRXsrWv1Hl0kQwoQlII4DwvrynhzL2p17WUPWPaTl/JBtWkbcrBz6oS2w7pAu5XXXfhHX1r8b/joUyi4Cz7oOgI1CA/BxC%2BLVaYE%2B9vRqnIWhr84gKExsMvJF6viij2GZVsAXN01WMnqCYICgktwbM0Y4z2c%2Bxo8p1vwWIiAIAcOlKydrNGEMGcwffVSToQ0xktgyqaEO3KQ%2BOzB6KwOjE0uRPkBackTAyZUxTHRtN/bStjSRqvGzeIOIzOXtJheucv7iOEbSwAgVMdBCLKJ698ugtBri%2BELAd6C6fCHQ/n2HJO7ddRIeUGpJPMCljTSUg81Gbb7T0sMswMb%2BhM6CtmIR5K6rsIaDP1TgDZEOXa2Bg7j%2BuKl3qQ8CZRhm5Nx1pWAHimIO/j/7UF#\">include the reduction of MSC&rsquo;s qualifying criteria&nbsp;</a>to allow tech startups to enjoy the same benefits as some of the biggest tech companies in Malaysia.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Also Read:&nbsp;<a href=\"https://s3-ap-southeast-1.amazonaws.com/xremo.com.my/blog-article-there-no-such-thing-as-an-original-idea-and_9-other-lessons-msian-startups-taught-me.html?X-Amz-Date=20160214T135245Z&amp;X-Amz-Expires=300&amp;X-Amz-Algorithm=AWS4-HMAC-SHA256&amp;X-Amz-Signature=bb57f4cf5b54fc431f298828e3468aaf036699caa675c8cabd39deec3db6f8d2&amp;X-Amz-Credential=ASIAIZV2KXWN4LIRWHDQ/20160214/ap-southeast-1/s3/aws4_request&amp;X-Amz-SignedHeaders=Host&amp;x-amz-security-token=AQoDYXdzEFQakAPxCOWTa5/XPgGqdq4iKPRJ8tMrT9kEncvBJWjh2gf43lNGtI%2Bnjoif3tKYDZ9g0ofIB4vOg59iIYiHf3nbdvdu%2BdBbfE6yoXhWZVhCY%2BxeoAX07oTgGCQkSMVXfMxatzGSJtJ7/JVJdUobvjRXsrWv1Hl0kQwoQlII4DwvrynhzL2p17WUPWPaTl/JBtWkbcrBz6oS2w7pAu5XXXfhHX1r8b/joUyi4Cz7oOgI1CA/BxC%2BLVaYE%2B9vRqnIWhr84gKExsMvJF6viij2GZVsAXN01WMnqCYICgktwbM0Y4z2c%2Bxo8p1vwWIiAIAcOlKydrNGEMGcwffVSToQ0xktgyqaEO3KQ%2BOzB6KwOjE0uRPkBackTAyZUxTHRtN/bStjSRqvGzeIOIzOXtJheucv7iOEbSwAgVMdBCLKJ698ugtBri%2BELAd6C6fCHQ/n2HJO7ddRIeUGpJPMCljTSUg81Gbb7T0sMswMb%2BhM6CtmIR5K6rsIaDP1TgDZEOXa2Bg7j%2BuKl3qQ8CZRhm5Nx1pWAHimIO/j/7UF#\">Two Lifelong Friends Spill On Their Unusual Spectacle Business And Why One Pair Is Never Enough</a></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<h3>3. Life As A Developer Is Tough</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><img src=\"https://s3-ap-southeast-1.amazonaws.com/xremo.com.my/img/blog/there_no_such_thing_as_an_original_idea_and_9_other_lessons_msian_startups_taught_me/code-division-programmers-hard-at-work.jpg\" /><em>Programmers hard at work (Image Credit: Jeremy Ong)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Seriously, developers and programmers do not get enough credit for what they do. Before attending&nbsp;<a href=\"https://s3-ap-southeast-1.amazonaws.com/xremo.com.my/blog-article-there-no-such-thing-as-an-original-idea-and_9-other-lessons-msian-startups-taught-me.html?X-Amz-Date=20160214T135245Z&amp;X-Amz-Expires=300&amp;X-Amz-Algorithm=AWS4-HMAC-SHA256&amp;X-Amz-Signature=bb57f4cf5b54fc431f298828e3468aaf036699caa675c8cabd39deec3db6f8d2&amp;X-Amz-Credential=ASIAIZV2KXWN4LIRWHDQ/20160214/ap-southeast-1/s3/aws4_request&amp;X-Amz-SignedHeaders=Host&amp;x-amz-security-token=AQoDYXdzEFQakAPxCOWTa5/XPgGqdq4iKPRJ8tMrT9kEncvBJWjh2gf43lNGtI%2Bnjoif3tKYDZ9g0ofIB4vOg59iIYiHf3nbdvdu%2BdBbfE6yoXhWZVhCY%2BxeoAX07oTgGCQkSMVXfMxatzGSJtJ7/JVJdUobvjRXsrWv1Hl0kQwoQlII4DwvrynhzL2p17WUPWPaTl/JBtWkbcrBz6oS2w7pAu5XXXfhHX1r8b/joUyi4Cz7oOgI1CA/BxC%2BLVaYE%2B9vRqnIWhr84gKExsMvJF6viij2GZVsAXN01WMnqCYICgktwbM0Y4z2c%2Bxo8p1vwWIiAIAcOlKydrNGEMGcwffVSToQ0xktgyqaEO3KQ%2BOzB6KwOjE0uRPkBackTAyZUxTHRtN/bStjSRqvGzeIOIzOXtJheucv7iOEbSwAgVMdBCLKJ698ugtBri%2BELAd6C6fCHQ/n2HJO7ddRIeUGpJPMCljTSUg81Gbb7T0sMswMb%2BhM6CtmIR5K6rsIaDP1TgDZEOXa2Bg7j%2BuKl3qQ8CZRhm5Nx1pWAHimIO/j/7UF#\">MaGIC&rsquo;s Web Development Bootcamp&nbsp;</a>, I have always wondered what was going on in the minds of the techies I meet. Well, now I know, the bootcamp made me cringe every single day and is one of the top 10 hardest things I have done in my entire life, but boy, was it rewarding. Now I see developers in a different light, they&rsquo;re cool and super-intelligent people.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So the next time you are hiring a developer, treat them as such. If you treat them like assembly line workers, the quality of your software/project/website will decline. They tend to be introverted so sit them down regularly and talk to them, understand them better and you will find it extremely rewarding!</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>4. You Don&rsquo;t Need A Lot Of Financial Capital (What You Really Need Is Human Capital)</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Brilliant startups rarely have enough capital, but they almost always have an awesome and committed team. Awesome people are everywhere in Malaysia, the key challenge I faced was finding a team member that shared the same vision. When you&rsquo;re from a business background like I am, it is absolutely necessary to obtain a superb technical co-founder that believes in your startup!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This is especially true in Malaysia in the context of finding technical co-founders. We have brilliant ideas but most of us lack access to the talents who are capable of executing these very ideas (which is the basis that MaGIC&rsquo;s Web Development Bootcamp is built upon).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So if you already have a technical co-founder who shares your ambition, cherish them like they&rsquo;re your one and only love. Otherwise, keep looking!</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>5. Dealing With Your Boss Is Tough, Building A Startup Is At Least 10 Times Tougher</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><img src=\"https://s3-ap-southeast-1.amazonaws.com/xremo.com.my/img/blog/there_no_such_thing_as_an_original_idea_and_9_other_lessons_msian_startups_taught_me/startup-vs-boss-e1438832456495.png\" /><em>Image Credit: www.entrepreneurfail.com</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you think that dealing with anal bosses and clients is tough, building a startup is WAY harder. At least you get a stable pay check, clear work direction (most of the time) and clearly defined roles. Conference speakers and articles on the internet often discuss startups as if they were simple projects, like the ones you work on in universities or even colleges.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Remember the friendly sales guy, your mean HR lady and the dorky finance dude? Working on a startup means you have to take on ALL these roles at once! The bright side is that working on a startup, you learn the ins and outs of how difficult it is to run a startup. Building the first product&mdash;hard; fundraising&mdash;hard; finding the right partner&mdash;super hard. Even with great support from MaGIC and my mentors, I have yet to discover the point at which life becomes easier.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Also Read:&nbsp;<a href=\"https://s3-ap-southeast-1.amazonaws.com/xremo.com.my/blog-article-there-no-such-thing-as-an-original-idea-and_9-other-lessons-msian-startups-taught-me.html?X-Amz-Date=20160214T135245Z&amp;X-Amz-Expires=300&amp;X-Amz-Algorithm=AWS4-HMAC-SHA256&amp;X-Amz-Signature=bb57f4cf5b54fc431f298828e3468aaf036699caa675c8cabd39deec3db6f8d2&amp;X-Amz-Credential=ASIAIZV2KXWN4LIRWHDQ/20160214/ap-southeast-1/s3/aws4_request&amp;X-Amz-SignedHeaders=Host&amp;x-amz-security-token=AQoDYXdzEFQakAPxCOWTa5/XPgGqdq4iKPRJ8tMrT9kEncvBJWjh2gf43lNGtI%2Bnjoif3tKYDZ9g0ofIB4vOg59iIYiHf3nbdvdu%2BdBbfE6yoXhWZVhCY%2BxeoAX07oTgGCQkSMVXfMxatzGSJtJ7/JVJdUobvjRXsrWv1Hl0kQwoQlII4DwvrynhzL2p17WUPWPaTl/JBtWkbcrBz6oS2w7pAu5XXXfhHX1r8b/joUyi4Cz7oOgI1CA/BxC%2BLVaYE%2B9vRqnIWhr84gKExsMvJF6viij2GZVsAXN01WMnqCYICgktwbM0Y4z2c%2Bxo8p1vwWIiAIAcOlKydrNGEMGcwffVSToQ0xktgyqaEO3KQ%2BOzB6KwOjE0uRPkBackTAyZUxTHRtN/bStjSRqvGzeIOIzOXtJheucv7iOEbSwAgVMdBCLKJ698ugtBri%2BELAd6C6fCHQ/n2HJO7ddRIeUGpJPMCljTSUg81Gbb7T0sMswMb%2BhM6CtmIR5K6rsIaDP1TgDZEOXa2Bg7j%2BuKl3qQ8CZRhm5Nx1pWAHimIO/j/7UF#\">MaGIC&rsquo;s Accelerator Program Is Not Just A Program&mdash;It&rsquo;s A Potential Life Changer</a></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<h3>6. Work-Life Balance Is A Mythical Unicorn</h3>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p>&ldquo;There is no such thing as work-life balance. Everything worth fighting for unbalances your life.&rdquo; &ndash; Alain de Botton</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\n<p>Running a startup is very much like giving your life away. Your startup becomes your life, and very soon you will be working weekends and weeknights voluntarily. Be ready to get rid of the sense of entitlement. You&rsquo;ll soon realise that the experience of running a startup is cold and cruel.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img src=\"https://s3-ap-southeast-1.amazonaws.com/xremo.com.my/img/blog/there_no_such_thing_as_an_original_idea_and_9_other_lessons_msian_startups_taught_me/img_4054-e1438832991429.jpg\" /><em>Image Credit: http://philipbloom.net/blog/worklife-2/</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The experience is exhilarating and life gets very tiring at times, but it is also oddly gratifying. There is nothing like spending days and nights building your product, launching it into the market and having your first subscription or order. That being said, it is important to find time to rest and recuperate.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>7. Have Enough Money To Survive For At Least 1 Year (Then Multiply It By 3)</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>People tend to underestimate the costs of creating and running a startup, which is especially true when you come from an employment background like myself. Many fledgling founders do not have at least a year&rsquo;s worth of savings to free their schedule up to do months of unpaid legwork.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The reason I suggest multiplying your savings by 3 is because there are bound to be tons of costs that you may not foresee as a first time founder. Examples of these costs include data gathering, prototyping, marketing costs, legal fees, and self development.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you have enough seed funding to kickstart this process, good for you! You can outsource these tasks, but keep in mind that managing the project according to your specifications is a gargantuan task and executing these tasks would probably be more expensive than initially budgeted. Identify key roles to hire, and in-source it for better management.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img src=\"https://s3-ap-southeast-1.amazonaws.com/xremo.com.my/img/blog/there_no_such_thing_as_an_original_idea_and_9_other_lessons_msian_startups_taught_me/funding-e1438833304345.jpg\" /><em>Image Credit: http://sv.tie.org</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you are bootstrapping a business that operates at a loss in the first 6 months without any seed investors, funding comes from you and/or your partners. I suggest assembling a team of like-minded people and budget a bigger chunk into self development and tools to help with the team&rsquo;s productivity instead. Your team members should also be relatively stable in terms of finances so that they are able to commit themselves fully into running a startup.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>8. Balance Product Development &amp; Networking</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Most startup founders dive right into it focusing a lot on their vision of the product and burn through 100% of their resources on product development. In my short exposure in the community, I discovered a pattern. Founders of early-stage startups allocate equal amounts of time into networking and development. Have a working calendar to effectively allocate half your time attending events and the other half into developing the product.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Having said that, it is also important to be more selective with attending events. Having a clear goal on why you want to meet people can help guide your decision-making process. Are you looking for investors? Or are you looking for a potential co-founder? Ask yourself these questions and start narrowing down event selection.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Be open, you can learn so many things from just talking to people at events. More often than not, these people can teach you something or you can derive some sort of strategic benefit. You never know who you might bump into at such events. Don&rsquo;t be shy, identify people who can provide valuable insights and value. Add them on Facebook or follow them on Twitter!</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Also Read:&nbsp;<a href=\"https://s3-ap-southeast-1.amazonaws.com/xremo.com.my/blog-article-there-no-such-thing-as-an-original-idea-and_9-other-lessons-msian-startups-taught-me.html?X-Amz-Date=20160214T135245Z&amp;X-Amz-Expires=300&amp;X-Amz-Algorithm=AWS4-HMAC-SHA256&amp;X-Amz-Signature=bb57f4cf5b54fc431f298828e3468aaf036699caa675c8cabd39deec3db6f8d2&amp;X-Amz-Credential=ASIAIZV2KXWN4LIRWHDQ/20160214/ap-southeast-1/s3/aws4_request&amp;X-Amz-SignedHeaders=Host&amp;x-amz-security-token=AQoDYXdzEFQakAPxCOWTa5/XPgGqdq4iKPRJ8tMrT9kEncvBJWjh2gf43lNGtI%2Bnjoif3tKYDZ9g0ofIB4vOg59iIYiHf3nbdvdu%2BdBbfE6yoXhWZVhCY%2BxeoAX07oTgGCQkSMVXfMxatzGSJtJ7/JVJdUobvjRXsrWv1Hl0kQwoQlII4DwvrynhzL2p17WUPWPaTl/JBtWkbcrBz6oS2w7pAu5XXXfhHX1r8b/joUyi4Cz7oOgI1CA/BxC%2BLVaYE%2B9vRqnIWhr84gKExsMvJF6viij2GZVsAXN01WMnqCYICgktwbM0Y4z2c%2Bxo8p1vwWIiAIAcOlKydrNGEMGcwffVSToQ0xktgyqaEO3KQ%2BOzB6KwOjE0uRPkBackTAyZUxTHRtN/bStjSRqvGzeIOIzOXtJheucv7iOEbSwAgVMdBCLKJ698ugtBri%2BELAd6C6fCHQ/n2HJO7ddRIeUGpJPMCljTSUg81Gbb7T0sMswMb%2BhM6CtmIR5K6rsIaDP1TgDZEOXa2Bg7j%2BuKl3qQ8CZRhm5Nx1pWAHimIO/j/7UF#\">These 12 Caf&eacute;s In Klang Valley With Free WiFi And Power Sockets Are Professional Nomads&rsquo; Best Bet</a></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<h3>9. For Your Startup To Grow, You Have To Grow</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><img src=\"https://s3-ap-southeast-1.amazonaws.com/xremo.com.my/img/blog/there_no_such_thing_as_an_original_idea_and_9_other_lessons_msian_startups_taught_me/awesome-graduates-from-code-division1-e1438833140357.jpg\" /><em>Graduates from Code Division (Image Credit: Jeremy Ong)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Rather than focusing blindly on building and growing the company itself, a new founder is better served spending equal time and energy to improve his or herself. When you pour tons of resources and time into building your business and it fails, the only thing that stays with you is the learnings that you have derived from the process of building it.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Everyone says they are busy, but founders have to cut through the clutter and eliminate lesser tasks by focusing on meeting the business&rsquo; and their own bigger goals.</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p>&ldquo;If you really want to know where your destiny lies, look at where you apply your time.&rdquo; &ndash; Mark Cuban</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\n<p>This gets back to saying &lsquo;no&rsquo; to many people and focusing on what you hold true. Stress on the importance of focusing on what you are building and make it really good at what it does. This also includes developing certain skill sets and mental fortitude as a founder that will assist you in future endeavours.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>10. There Is No Such Thing As An Original Idea Or A Perfect Product</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>If you think you have an original idea, the chances are someone has thought of it before.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This is a cold hard truth that I have learnt in my journey but should not be taken as a discouragement to start something of your own. The key is to have a stronger team, which leads to better planning and execution.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img src=\"https://s3-ap-southeast-1.amazonaws.com/xremo.com.my/img/blog/there_no_such_thing_as_an_original_idea_and_9_other_lessons_msian_startups_taught_me/fb_vs_fs.png\" /><em>Image Credit: http://arayofray125.blogspot.com</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The presence of a booming social media platform like Friendster did not deter Facebook from doing the same thing. Facebook started off as a Friendster clone and by focusing on key engineering hiring (stronger team), it improved the user experience to be more intuitive and developed APIs to encourage other developers to leverage on the platform Facebook provides (planning and execution).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Even right now, Facebook pushes multiple update patches per day that &ldquo;improves&rdquo; their product based on user data that they have collected.</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p>Perfect Product = Innovation &amp; Constant Improvement</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\n<p>To reiterate, there is no such thing as a perfect product, or even the likes of it. Once this has been understood, then it will be easier for you to understand that there is&hellip;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&hellip;no such thing as a perfect startup. All successful startups are built upon heavy refinement and optimisation of processes over a long period of time. The key is to start somewhere and learn along the way.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Also Read:&nbsp;<a href=\"https://s3-ap-southeast-1.amazonaws.com/xremo.com.my/blog-article-there-no-such-thing-as-an-original-idea-and_9-other-lessons-msian-startups-taught-me.html?X-Amz-Date=20160214T135245Z&amp;X-Amz-Expires=300&amp;X-Amz-Algorithm=AWS4-HMAC-SHA256&amp;X-Amz-Signature=bb57f4cf5b54fc431f298828e3468aaf036699caa675c8cabd39deec3db6f8d2&amp;X-Amz-Credential=ASIAIZV2KXWN4LIRWHDQ/20160214/ap-southeast-1/s3/aws4_request&amp;X-Amz-SignedHeaders=Host&amp;x-amz-security-token=AQoDYXdzEFQakAPxCOWTa5/XPgGqdq4iKPRJ8tMrT9kEncvBJWjh2gf43lNGtI%2Bnjoif3tKYDZ9g0ofIB4vOg59iIYiHf3nbdvdu%2BdBbfE6yoXhWZVhCY%2BxeoAX07oTgGCQkSMVXfMxatzGSJtJ7/JVJdUobvjRXsrWv1Hl0kQwoQlII4DwvrynhzL2p17WUPWPaTl/JBtWkbcrBz6oS2w7pAu5XXXfhHX1r8b/joUyi4Cz7oOgI1CA/BxC%2BLVaYE%2B9vRqnIWhr84gKExsMvJF6viij2GZVsAXN01WMnqCYICgktwbM0Y4z2c%2Bxo8p1vwWIiAIAcOlKydrNGEMGcwffVSToQ0xktgyqaEO3KQ%2BOzB6KwOjE0uRPkBackTAyZUxTHRtN/bStjSRqvGzeIOIzOXtJheucv7iOEbSwAgVMdBCLKJ698ugtBri%2BELAd6C6fCHQ/n2HJO7ddRIeUGpJPMCljTSUg81Gbb7T0sMswMb%2BhM6CtmIR5K6rsIaDP1TgDZEOXa2Bg7j%2BuKl3qQ8CZRhm5Nx1pWAHimIO/j/7UF#\">The Glaring Differences Between Uber And GrabCar, And Why I Chose The Latter</a></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>This article is originally titled &ldquo;10 things I learned jumping into the Malaysian startup community&rdquo; and you can read the full original article&nbsp;<a href=\"https://s3-ap-southeast-1.amazonaws.com/xremo.com.my/blog-article-there-no-such-thing-as-an-original-idea-and_9-other-lessons-msian-startups-taught-me.html?X-Amz-Date=20160214T135245Z&amp;X-Amz-Expires=300&amp;X-Amz-Algorithm=AWS4-HMAC-SHA256&amp;X-Amz-Signature=bb57f4cf5b54fc431f298828e3468aaf036699caa675c8cabd39deec3db6f8d2&amp;X-Amz-Credential=ASIAIZV2KXWN4LIRWHDQ/20160214/ap-southeast-1/s3/aws4_request&amp;X-Amz-SignedHeaders=Host&amp;x-amz-security-token=AQoDYXdzEFQakAPxCOWTa5/XPgGqdq4iKPRJ8tMrT9kEncvBJWjh2gf43lNGtI%2Bnjoif3tKYDZ9g0ofIB4vOg59iIYiHf3nbdvdu%2BdBbfE6yoXhWZVhCY%2BxeoAX07oTgGCQkSMVXfMxatzGSJtJ7/JVJdUobvjRXsrWv1Hl0kQwoQlII4DwvrynhzL2p17WUPWPaTl/JBtWkbcrBz6oS2w7pAu5XXXfhHX1r8b/joUyi4Cz7oOgI1CA/BxC%2BLVaYE%2B9vRqnIWhr84gKExsMvJF6viij2GZVsAXN01WMnqCYICgktwbM0Y4z2c%2Bxo8p1vwWIiAIAcOlKydrNGEMGcwffVSToQ0xktgyqaEO3KQ%2BOzB6KwOjE0uRPkBackTAyZUxTHRtN/bStjSRqvGzeIOIzOXtJheucv7iOEbSwAgVMdBCLKJ698ugtBri%2BELAd6C6fCHQ/n2HJO7ddRIeUGpJPMCljTSUg81Gbb7T0sMswMb%2BhM6CtmIR5K6rsIaDP1TgDZEOXa2Bg7j%2BuKl3qQ8CZRhm5Nx1pWAHimIO/j/7UF#\">here&nbsp;</a>. It is republished with permission.</em></p>\r\n', '2016-02-14 06:51:25', '2016-02-19 08:29:49', '“Are you crazy? How’re you going to survive without a steady income?” That was what majority of my family members told me when I told them I wanted to quit my job and do something of my own. Ever since I graduated, I have always worked in a corporate Fast Moving Consumer Goods (FMCG) environment as a marketer. ', '', 'Jeremy Wong', '', 4),
(5, 'The facts you must know before starting your Café business in KL', 'the-facts-you-must-know-before-starting-your-caf-business-in-kl', '<p>The cafe scene in Malaysia is thriving although we still have much work to do. The pioneers of the scene from just 5 years ago were often inspired by the vibrant Australian cafe scene. Melbourne in particular has been at the heart of a culinary revolution that covers &ldquo;artisanal&rdquo; pastries, seasonal produce, beer and coffee.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Today, we have Western-style cafes with a Malaysian flavor.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The local independent coffee cafe scene has a rather daunting churn rate (excluding chain/franchise cafes). In a 12 month period, 3 out of 10 cafes will close. In a 30 month period, the rate worsens to 6 out of 10. This churn applies to the areas covered by MBSJ-MBPJ.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Yes, it is horrible. Here are some of the common pitfalls to avoid. Note that these are specific to the problems in the Klang Valley.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>What is your Unique Selling Point</h3>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>What is going to persuade customers to visit you instead of the other guy down the street? What is going to bring them back to you over and over again? This is a business and there are only so many Ringgits to go around. A unique selling point is going to make a big difference between 2 tables full and a full house.</li>\r\n	<li>Your USP can be anything from interior design to food to a special service. For example:\r\n	<p><img src=\"https://s3-ap-southeast-1.amazonaws.com/xremo.com.my/img/blog/the_facts_you_must_know_before_starting_your_cafe_business_in_kl/coffee-cottage.jpg\" /></p>\r\n\r\n	<p><img src=\"https://s3-ap-southeast-1.amazonaws.com/xremo.com.my/img/blog/the_facts_you_must_know_before_starting_your_cafe_business_in_kl/upstairs-cafe.jpg\" /></p>\r\n\r\n	<ol>\r\n		<li>Barks and Bunnies / Hop-Hop Cafe - dog friendly, has bunnies</li>\r\n		<li>Coffee Cottage - has a cat section</li>\r\n		<li>MorningWood - has celebrity patronage; do not doubt the power of handsome men and beautiful women serving coffee</li>\r\n		<li>Lorem Ipsum - artists&rsquo; cafe with paint and canvases available.</li>\r\n		<li>Upstairs Cafe - cheap western eats in a cafe setting, good cakes</li>\r\n	</ol>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h3>Location-Location-LOCATION</h3>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Urban-scapes being what it is, you&rsquo;ll find significant traffic improvements with the right location. Popular shopping malls have high rents but the walk traffic can be worth it. Lower tier shopping malls? Make sure your pricing is reasonable.</li>\r\n	<li>Another interesting thing to note about this matter is this; people are more likely to spend in an upscale shopping mall but more thrifty in a less flashy one. And this extends into the cafe. Better interiors mean more willingness to spend on food and drink.</li>\r\n	<li>Also note, a location can cater to several market segments; college/university students, professionals, newly married, young parents, etc. It is up to you to do your homework and get your business to target the best segments.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h3>Residential Property is RESIDENTIAL. Not COMMERCIAL</h3>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Stop screwing around with the local council. If you think you can build your cafe on residential property and then persuade the council into giving you a business certificate just because you&rsquo;ve already plowed all the investment a here&rsquo;s-some-donation, you&rsquo;re going to be disappointed and poorer. And a donation short.</li>\r\n	<li>Also note that some council-people are unscrupulous. I&rsquo;ve heard stories about council-people telling a business owner to proceed with renovations at a residential bungalow and a review will be done after. The assumption being that approval can be obtained. Don&rsquo;t be fooled. You must get WRITTEN approval to convert residential title to temporary commercial title FIRST. If you don&rsquo;t, you&rsquo;re just setting yourself up for more &ldquo;donation&rdquo; opportunities.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h3>Town Council renovation and business license approvals</h3>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Town councils print out application booklets that are in-depth and easy to use. With MBSA and MBSJ, these booklets cost you about RM 50 but explains in depth what you need to get the required approvals and licenses. Follow instructions, fill out the booklet as required. A council-person will run through the necessary pages with you. If your application is missing something, that&rsquo;s for you to follow through. It isn&rsquo;t for the council-person to listen to you bitch about how complicated and tedious the procedures are.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h3>Capital for 1 year of operation</h3>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Including renovations and furnishings, the minimum is to have at least 1 year of operating funds in hand. This means enough money to pay rent, utilities and salaries. If you don&rsquo;t, then don&rsquo;t start. The 1 year mark is the necessary point to allow people in your general vicinity to get to know you and grow your reputation. It also gives you the breathing room to do what you need to be doing; focusing on service standards, food-drink quality and marketing activities.</li>\r\n	<li>And for goodness sake, pay yourself. Whoever works at the cafe must takei&gt;a wage - even if you are a director or shareholder.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h3>Work with right people- Sometimes human capital is more difficult to get than financial capital</h3>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Unfortunately, this is the most difficult advice to follow. Many cafes have failed due to issues between partners and between owners and their expectations. If you cannot work with a person, be gracious and part ways as amicably as you can.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n', '2016-02-14 07:03:56', '2016-02-19 08:29:24', 'The cafe scene in Malaysia is thriving although we still have much work to do. The pioneers of the scene from just 5 years ago were often inspired by the vibrant Australian cafe scene. Melbourne in particular has been at the heart of a culinary revolution that covers “artisanal” pastries, seasonal produce, beer and coffee.', '', 'Roy Goh', '', 4),
(7, 'How to win the trust from your boss?', 'how-to-win-the-trust-from-your-boss', '<p>One research conducted by Randstrd in 2014 shown the critical fact that up to 70% of employees are planning to leave their jobs, and one major reason is they don&rsquo;t gain trust from senior managers. But why don&rsquo;t they trust? If they don&rsquo;y trust own employees, and who will do the things? The seniors are putting themselves into an self-directed-paradox.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are actually some tips for senior managers to learn how in identify the trustworth employees, how to trust, how to show trust approperly, and how to maximise the result via using trust. But all thing happens because of both sides, and now, an equally important issue needed to be address, which is as employees, &ldquo;HOW CAN YOU WIN THE TRUST FROM YOUR BOSS?&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Guys, the number zero rule is &ldquo;Trust is not to be given, is to be earned&rdquo;. We must fight for the trust, instead of waiting one day my boss will realize I can be trusted. So reset your mindset, and start to work out how to earn the trust. And luckly, here are some tips for you:</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>#1: Be humble, open minded</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Be humble is the number one thing you need to do, because this is a way to show you are open minded with instructions and suggestions, and you are also willing to keep learning. This is very important for bosses to feel certain that the tasks you are doing will go along a healthy direction and lead into a promising result. The humble attitude is a guarentee to managers about their ability to perticipate the result, to guide and manage the quality. So want your boss to trust you, be humble is the first rule.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img src=\"https://s3-ap-southeast-1.amazonaws.com/xremo.com.my/img/blog/how_to_win_the_trust_from_your_boss/a29fb912013b70637cbe509646c9b233.jpeg\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<h3>#2: More communication</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Trust start from knowing. So If you expect somebody know you, start communication first, specially with your boss. Don&rsquo;t wait for him/her to initiate the conversation, be procative. Using a smart start to ease into, choose right topic which can show your profession and value for the company to standout yourself from passive employees, choose a right time so you and your boss can have a decent discussion, and leave a good impression to your boss so he/she can remember you.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img src=\"https://s3-ap-southeast-1.amazonaws.com/xremo.com.my/img/blog/how_to_win_the_trust_from_your_boss/2009-08-14-communication-is-key.png\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<h3>#3: &ldquo;Let me do&rdquo;, show your attitude</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Understand your boss as a thinker, and you are the solution. So you need to volunteerly take care of the things that matters to the business and to your boss. So raise up your hand and say &ldquo;Let me do&rdquo;. Your boss dones&rsquo;t need somebody who escapes from problem. And because you are willing to do, you will build up valuable experience, which is important to create trust. You will experience many things, understand from different angles, and think in different ways..</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>#4: Be responsible and care, show your quality</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>The responsible and care is very important for building the trust. Only you are responsible, so you will be careful for your behavior and consiquences. Care means you will treat things seriously. That why your boss is willing to give you some important and challenging tasks, &rsquo;cause they know you will treat the tasks and company seriously and commit to the good result from tasks. This is mental qualification of being trusted.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img src=\"https://s3-ap-southeast-1.amazonaws.com/xremo.com.my/img/blog/how_to_win_the_trust_from_your_boss/not-me-penguins-of-madagascar-18270082-470-349.jpg\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<h3>#5: Keep growing, be prepared</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Don&rsquo;t be too aggressive, and don&rsquo;t expect trust will build in one shot. It takes time. But don&rsquo;t give up, and don&rsquo;t think all the efforts are waste of time, because you cannot start nurish trust right before you need it. Stick into the tips before, and keep developing yourself, growing your strength, so you will less likely blow your moment when it comes to you.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img src=\"https://s3-ap-southeast-1.amazonaws.com/xremo.com.my/img/blog/how_to_win_the_trust_from_your_boss/og1efjsqbnlupcbqrcdt.jpg\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The boss need one key player who care about the business, prepare to get problem solved, always have open mind for suggestions or guidance, and be responsible for results. This is the fomular to create the trust between you and your boss. So, practice this, and good luck!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Do you have any question or problem at your work place? Or you have expetienced something and would like to share with us? Contact us now and get yourself heard!!</p>\r\n', '2016-02-14 07:06:39', '2016-02-14 07:26:14', 'One research conducted by Randstrd in 2014 shown the critical fact that up to 70% of employees are planning to leave their jobs, and one major reason is they don’t gain trust from senior managers. But why don’t they trust? If they don’y trust own employees, and who will do the things? The seniors are putting themselves into an self-directed-paradox.', '', 'XREMO', '', 4);
